247
00:15:18,700 --> 00:15:24,940
There have been several papers that have come out that are pointing to individual options,

248
00:15:24,940 --> 00:15:27,380
but none have been put into clinical practice.

249
00:15:27,380 --> 00:15:31,940
None have been shown to really validate consumption in a meaningful way.

250
00:15:31,940 --> 00:15:36,260
So at this point in time, we don't have that for consumption.

251
00:15:36,260 --> 00:15:43,020
What we do have are some indirect measures of fructose, shall we say, biotoxicity.

252
00:15:43,020 --> 00:15:46,900
Yeah, like uric acid or ALT would be two examples.

253
00:15:46,900 --> 00:15:50,820
Those are the ones I was going to bring up, exactly, uric acid and ALT.

254
00:15:50,820 --> 00:15:57,720
So we know that the more sugar you consume, the higher your serum uric acid goes and the

255
00:15:57,720 --> 00:16:00,340
more risk you have for gout.

256
00:16:00,340 --> 00:16:04,380
Benjamin Franklin knew that and wrote about it.

257
00:16:04,380 --> 00:16:10,620
The reason that happens is because since fructose can only be metabolized in the liver

258
00:16:10,620 --> 00:16:17,700
because the liver has the Glut5 transporter, every time a fructose molecule enters a liver

259
00:16:17,700 --> 00:16:19,820
cell, it has to be phosphorylated.

260
00:16:19,820 --> 00:16:25,700
So it goes from fructose to fructose 1 phosphate and the enzyme that does that is called fructose

261
00:16:25,700 --> 00:16:26,700
kinase.

262
00:16:26,700 --> 00:16:31,640
Well, the phosphate has to be donated and ATP is the donor.

263
00:16:31,640 --> 00:16:37,960
So ATP becomes ADP, adenosine triphosphate becomes adenosine diphosphate.

264
00:16:37,960 --> 00:16:45,660
Now there is a scavenger enzyme in the liver called adenosine deaminase 1.

265
00:16:45,660 --> 00:16:51,520
And what it does is it then takes ADP down to AMP, monophosphate, then to IMP, inositol

266
00:16:51,520 --> 00:16:54,640
monophosphate, and finally to uric acid.

267
00:16:54,640 --> 00:17:01,600
So the uric acid concentration in the blood is a proxy for total fructose consumption.

268
00:17:01,600 --> 00:17:04,800
Now there are other things that make uric acid go up too, like protein.

269
00:17:04,800 --> 00:17:08,720
But all things being equal, they do correlate with each other.

270
00:17:08,720 --> 00:17:13,520
And we've shown that serum uric acid in children and adolescents correlate with sugar beverage

271
00:17:13,520 --> 00:17:15,520
consumption, for instance.

272
00:17:15,520 --> 00:17:21,240
And other people have shown that that uric acid matters because uric acid is the inhibitor

273
00:17:21,240 --> 00:17:24,120
of endothelial nitric oxide synthase.

274
00:17:24,120 --> 00:17:31,760
That's an enzyme that exists in your vascular tree that vasodilates the blood vessels.

275
00:17:31,760 --> 00:17:33,880
And that keeps your blood pressure down.

276
00:17:33,880 --> 00:17:42,660
And we have shown that every increase by 10% in fructose consumption increases your blood

277
00:17:42,660 --> 00:17:46,660
pressure by 2 millimeters of mercury consistently.

278
00:17:46,660 --> 00:17:50,520
And that increases your risk of stroke by 10%.

279
00:17:50,520 --> 00:17:56,380
We have data, and it's also been shown by Dan Feig at UT San Antonio, that if you give

280
00:17:56,380 --> 00:18:01,720
an inhibitor of uric acid synthesis, allopurinol, which is what we give to gout patients, you

281
00:18:01,720 --> 00:18:06,760
can actually lower adolescents' blood pressures when they have essential hypertension.

282
00:18:06,760 --> 00:18:11,000
So this is a mechanistically valid problem.

283
00:18:11,000 --> 00:18:20,580
And it is a surrogate proxy biomarker sort of for sugar consumption.

